《Biography of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang》

Zhang Tingwei Shizhi was from Duya, courtesy name Ji. He had an elder brother named Zhong, with whom he lived together. He was appointed as a Qilai (a cavalry officer) based on his family's wealth, serving under Emperor Xiaowen of Han. For ten years he was not promoted and remained unknown. Shizhi said: "Long-term official service has diminished my brother's estate; I will not succeed." He wished to resign and return home. Zhonglangjiang Yuan Ang, knowing his virtue, regretted his departure, and thus requested to transfer Shizhi to the position of Yezhe (a court attendant). After Shizhi completed his morning duties, he brought forward suggestions for beneficial matters. Emperor Xiaowen said: "Speak modestly; do not raise overly lofty theories, but make them applicable for immediate implementation." Thus, Shizhi spoke at length about matters between the Qin and Han dynasties, explaining why Qin fell and why Han rose. Emperor Xiaowen praised him, and appointed Shizhi as Yezhe Puye (a high-ranking official in charge of the Yezhe department).

Shizhi accompanied the emperor on a journey and ascended the Tiger Circle (a menagerie). The emperor asked the Shanglin Wei (a forest official) about the inventory of birds and beasts; he asked over ten questions, but the official looked left and right and could not answer any. A Shifu (a supervisor of the Tiger Circle) from the side answered the emperor's questions about the birds and beasts inventory in great detail, intending to observe whether he could respond verbally without limit. Emperor Xiaowen said: "Should officials be like this? The Shanglin Wei is incompetent!" He thus ordered Shizhi to appoint the Shifu as Shanglin Ling (a forest official). Shizhi spoke before him: "Your Majesty, how do you regard Jiaohou Zhou Bo?" The emperor said: "He is a man of substance." He asked again: "How do you regard Dongyang Hou Zhang Xiang?" The emperor replied: "He is also a man of substance." Shizhi said: "Jiaohou and Dongyang Hou are both called 'men of substance'; yet these two could not utter a word when discussing affairs. How could they imitate this Shifu, who is deceitful, profit-seeking, and quick-witted? Moreover, Qin relied on clerks skilled in writing and legal documents; officials competed by being swift, harsh, and meticulous. However, the result was merely formalities, lacking any compassion in reality. Therefore, their faults were not heard, and they gradually declined until the Second Emperor, leading to the collapse of the world under the Qin. Now, Your Majesty promotes this Shifu solely because of his verbal eloquence and elevates him rapidly. I fear that the people will follow the wind, competing in verbal eloquence while lacking substance. Furthermore, the lower classes are influenced by the upper classes more quickly than by reflection; thus, choices and actions must be carefully considered." Emperor Xiaowen said: "Good." He thus stopped the appointment of the Shifu.

The emperor boarded his carriage and summoned Shizhi to ride beside him, walking slowly, and asked Shizhi about the faults of Qin. He reported everything truthfully. Upon arriving at the palace, the emperor appointed Shizhi as Gongsheng Ling (a public official in charge of imperial carriages).

Shortly thereafter, the Crown Prince and Prince Liang entered the court together in the same carriage, but did not descend at the Sima Gate. Thus, Shizhi chased them and stopped them from entering the palace gate. He then indicted them for disrespecting the public gate, and submitted the case. Princess Bo heard of this; Emperor Xiaowen removed his hat and apologized, saying: "I failed to teach my son properly." Princess Bo then sent an envoy to convey the imperial decree pardoning the Crown Prince and Prince Liang, after which they were allowed to enter. Emperor Xiaowen thus regarded Shizhi with admiration and appointed him as Zhong Dafu (a high-ranking official).

Shortly thereafter, Shizhi was promoted to Zhonglangjiang. He accompanied the emperor to Ba Ling, where he resided north of the latrine. At that time, Shen Fu accompanied the emperor; the emperor pointed out the Xinfeng Road to Shen Fu, saying: "This is the road to Handan." He had Shen Fu play the se, while the emperor leaned on the se and sang. Feeling melancholic and sorrowful, he turned to the ministers and said: "Alas! To bury the body in a coffin made of Northern Mountain stone, filled with hemp cotton, and lacquered between the layers—how could it be moved!" All around said: "Good." Shizhi stepped forward and said: "If there is something desirable within, even if confined to the Southern Mountain, there will still be a flaw; if there is nothing desirable within, even without a stone coffin, what sorrow is there?" Emperor Xiaowen praised him. Later, Shizhi was appointed as Tingwei (the chief judicial officer).

Shortly thereafter, the emperor went out over the Zhongwei Bridge. A person emerged from under the bridge, startling the imperial carriage horses. Thus, riders were sent to capture him, and he was brought before the Tingwei. Shizhi investigated the matter. The man said: "I am a countyman who came here; hearing of the imperial procession, I hid under the bridge. For a long time, I thought the procession had passed, so I emerged, saw the imperial carriage and horses, and ran away." The Tingwei Qin Dang ruled that one person violating the imperial procession should be fined. Emperor Xiaowen was angry and said: "This man startled my horse; my horse relied on its gentleness. If it were another horse, surely it would have injured me! Yet the Tingwei merely imposes a fine!" Shizhi said: "The law is what the emperor shares with the people for common use. Now that the law is thus, if we make it heavier, the law will lose credibility among the people. Moreover, at that time, if the emperor had ordered immediate execution, it would have been done. Now that the case has been submitted to the Tingwei, the Tingwei is the standard of justice for the world. If one inclination occurs, then the application of law throughout the world will become inconsistent; where will the people place their hands and feet? Only Your Majesty can discern this." After a long pause, the emperor said: "The Tingwei is correct."

Later, someone stole a jade ring placed before the high ancestral temple. He was captured, and Emperor Xiaowen was angry, submitting the case to the Tingwei for investigation. Shizhi examined the law and found that stealing articles of the ancestral temple and imperial use constituted a capital offense. He submitted the verdict for execution by public hanging. The emperor was greatly angry and said: "This man has no moral conduct; he stole an article from the ancestral temple of the late emperor. Those who submit cases to the Tingwei intend to have him executed by clan punishment, yet you submit it according to the law. This is not the intention with which we jointly uphold the ancestral temple." Shizhi removed his hat and bowed deeply, apologizing: "The law is thus sufficient. Moreover, the crimes are equal, yet distinctions are made based on right and wrong. Now, if someone steals an article from the ancestral temple and is executed by clan punishment, there is a one-in-a-million chance of injustice. Suppose a foolish commoner takes a handful of earth from Changling; how would Your Majesty add to his punishment?" For a long time, Emperor Xiaowen and Princess Bo discussed the matter, and thus permitted the Tingwei's verdict. At that time, Zhongwei Tiaohou Zhou Yafu and Prince Liang's Governor Shan Du Hou Wang Tiankai saw that Shizhi held a balanced view, and thus became close friends. Zhang Tingwei was thus renowned throughout the world.

After Emperor Xiaowen died, Emperor Jing took the throne. Shizhi feared, and claimed illness. He wished to resign, fearing severe punishment; he wished to apologize, but did not know how to proceed. Using Wang Sheng's advice, he finally went to apologize, and Emperor Jing did not accept it.

Wang Sheng was skilled in Yellow-Lao philosophy and was a recluse. Once summoned to stand in the court, the Three Dukes and Nine Ministers all gathered and stood. Wang Sheng, being an old man, said: "My socks are untied," and turned to Zhang Tingwei, saying: "Tie my socks for me!" Shizhi knelt and tied them. Afterward, someone told Wang Sheng: "Why did you humiliate Zhang Tingwei alone, making him kneel to tie your socks?" Wang Sheng said: "I am old and lowly; I judged that I would never benefit Zhang Tingwei. Zhang Tingwei is today a renowned official of the world; thus, I lightly humiliated the Tingwei, making him kneel to tie my socks, in order to honor him." The ministers heard this, admired Wang Sheng and regarded Zhang Tingwei with greater respect.

Zhang Tingwei served Emperor Jing for over a year, then became Governor of the Prince of Huainan, still bearing the former disgrace. For a long time, Shizhi died. His son was Zhang Zhi, courtesy name Changgong, who reached the rank of Dafu but was dismissed. He did not serve throughout his life because he could not seek favor with the contemporary world.

Feng Tang, whose grandfather was from Zhao, had his father moved to Dai. When Han rose, he was moved to Anling. Tang was noted for his filial piety, serving as head of the Zhonglang Bureau, and served under Emperor Xiaowen. When the emperor passed by, he asked Tang: "Old man, why do you serve as a Lang? Where is your home?" Tang answered truthfully. Emperor Xiaowen said: "When I resided in Dai, my High Food Supervisor Gao Qu often spoke of the virtue of Zhao General Li Qi, who fought at Julu. Now, every time I eat, my mind is never not on Julu. Do you know this?" Tang replied: "He is not as good as generals like Lian Po and Li Mu." The emperor asked: "Why?" Tang said: "My grandfather, when he was in Zhao, served as an officer (commander), and was good to Li Mu. My father formerly served as Dai Prime Minister, and was good to Zhao General Li Qi, knowing his character." After the emperor heard about Lian Po and Li Mu's character, he was greatly pleased, and pounded his thigh, saying: "Alas! If only I could have Lian Po and Li Mu as my generals, how could I worry about the Xiongnu!" Tang said: "Subject! Even if Your Majesty obtains Lian Po and Li Mu, You will not be able to use them." The emperor was angry, rose, and entered the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned Tang and rebuked him: "Why do you publicly insult me, with nowhere to hide?" Tang apologized, saying: "I am a rustic person who does not know how to avoid taboo words."

At that time, the Xiongnu had recently made a great incursion into Chaona, killing the Northern Earth Prefect Yang. The emperor, concerned about the Xiongnu raids, thus finally asked Tang again: "How do you know I cannot use Lian Po and Li Mu?" Tang replied: "I have heard that in ancient times, when kings dispatched generals, they knelt and pushed the carriage wheel, saying: 'Within the command, I control it; beyond the command, the general controls it. Military merit and rewards are all decided outside and reported back. This is not empty talk.' My grandfather said that Li Mu, as Zhao's general stationed on the border, used the market tax entirely to feed and reward his soldiers, and decided rewards outside, without interference from the center. He entrusted him and demanded success; thus, Li Mu was able to fully exert his intelligence and talent, dispatching 1,300 chariots, 13,000 cavalry, and 100,000 elite soldiers. This is why he drove the Chanyu north, defeated the Donghu, annihilated Danlin, suppressed the strong Qin in the west, and supported Han and Wei in the south. At that time, Zhao nearly became a hegemon. Later, when King Qian of Zhao ascended the throne, his mother was a courtesan. When Qian ascended, he used Guo Kai's slander, and finally executed Li Mu, ordering Yan Ju to replace him. Thus, the army was defeated, the soldiers fled north, and they were captured and annihilated by Qin. Now, I secretly hear that Wei Shang serves as Yunzhong Governor; he uses all the market tax to reward his soldiers, [and spends] private funds to raise cattle every five days to entertain guests, military officers, and attendants. Thus, the Xiongnu avoided far away, not approaching the border of Yunzhong. The enemy once entered, and Shang led chariots and cavalry to attack them, killing many of them. The soldiers are all commoners who joined the army from the fields; how could they know the length of the register or the unit symbols. All day long, they fought bravely, cutting heads and capturing enemies; when merit was reported to the command, if even one word did not correspond, the clerics used the law to punish them. The rewards were not implemented, while the clerics strictly enforced the law. I am foolish; I think Your Majesty's law is too clear, rewards too light, and punishments too heavy. Moreover, Yunzhong Governor Wei Shang was punished for having his merit count off the enemy by six ranks; Your Majesty submitted him to the clerics, stripped his title, and sentenced him to labor. From this, it is clear that even if Your Majesty obtains Lian Po and Li Mu, You will not be able to use them. I am truly foolish; I have touched upon taboo words; death, death!" Emperor Xiaowen was pleased. That day, he ordered Feng Tang to hold the imperial seal to pardon Wei Shang, restoring him as Yunzhong Governor, and appointed Tang as Cheqi Duwei (a high-ranking military officer), in charge of the Zhongwei and the chariot and cavalry of the commanderies and states.

In the seventh year, Emperor Jing took the throne, and appointed Tang as Governor of Chu, but later dismissed him. When Emperor Wu ascended, he sought virtuous and capable men, and recommended Feng Tang. At that time, Tang was over ninety years old and could no longer serve as an official; thus, Tang's son Feng Sui was appointed as a Lang. Sui's courtesy name was Wangsun, and he was also a remarkable man, and was friendly with me.

The Historian says: Zhang Ji's words on "men of substance" were to uphold the law without bending to personal will; Feng Gong's discussion on generals and commanders was full of flavor! Full of flavor! It is said: "Do not know a person, observe his friends." The two gentlemen's praises and commendations can be recorded in the hall and temple. The Book says: "Neither biased nor partisan, the Way is vast; neither partisan nor biased, the Way is smooth." Zhang Ji and Feng Gong are close to this. [end of text]


